english:
  title: Keeping to One's Station
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    All things have their appointed stations. The ox's station is to till the fields; the horse's station is to carry riders and burdens; the chicken's station is to herald the dawn; the dog's station is to guard through the night. When a creature fulfills its station, we say it keeps to its station. When it fails its duty and usurps another's role, we say it overreaches its station. To overstep one's station is to violate the natural order. To violate the natural order is to invite calamity.

    Consider a simple example: if a chicken does not crow at dawn but instead crows at dusk, all people would be startled and disturbed, and they would surely put an end to it. Is this not a calamity born of overreaching?

    I have observed in the households of gentlemen that male servants tend the fields and female servants work the loom. When the male servant farms and the female servant weaves, the household prospers. But if the male servant were to weave and the female servant to farm, all would regard it as strange and wrong. Who can say what calamity might follow?

    In the governance of a nation, the ministers and prime ministers must keep the station of ministers and prime ministers; the attendants and censors must keep the station of attendants and censors; the servants and lackeys must keep the station of servants and lackeys; the clerks and underlings must keep the station of clerks and underlings. When each fulfills their appointed role, the palace is ordered and the realm prospers. Yet if servants and lackeys were to assume the duties of ministers and prime ministers, if clerks and underlings were to usurp the role of censors and attendants, if ministers and censors abandoned their posts seeking to rise beyond their station—this is to overstep and violate the natural order. No misfortune could be greater.

    The sage Zhuangzi taught: "Though the cook may fail at his task, the priest who tends the altar never steps beyond it to take his place." This is wisdom profound.

    Of late, there arose a man of humble origin who, through fortunate circumstance, gained entry to high office and rose to the first rank. Though his station was not that of a censor, he assumed the censor's role. He delighted in writing memorials and attacking others. Once he presented a memorial assailing a great minister with bitter words, comparing him to Huo Guang and Liang Ji, and submitted this three or four times with no shame. Again he submitted memorials attacking the three highest ministers and six departments, claiming no worthy remained in court. He lorded over the officials and struck at the gentry as though he had gained great wisdom. Again he submitted a memorial against one of the emperor's attendants, calling him a base and contemptible creature, comparing him to Li Linfu, Lu Zhi, Jia Sidao, and Han Tuozhou. He threw himself before the palace gates, remonstrating with the throne more fiercely than any proper censor.

    When I heard of this, I laughed and said: "This man has merit, he has talent, he has learning. But he loves to overstep his station and judge all matters. I fear he will meet the fate of the chicken that crows at night—destruction."

    Not long after, the factions in court were found to have corrupted the realm. Connected to a powerful faction, he had fabricated charges against others and submitted false memorials. For this, his honors were stripped and he was exiled to a distant place. All said: "This is the calamity of overreaching one's station."

    Therefore do the wise revere those who keep faithfully to their post.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to "南華老仙" (the sage Zhuangzi) quotes a passage about the cook and the ritual priest to illustrate that each profession should remain within its proper sphere.
    - The historical figures mentioned—Huo Guang, Liang Ji, Li Linfu, Lu Zhi, Jia Sidao, and Han Tuozhou—were all powerful officials known for corrupting governance and overreaching their authority.
    - This essay appears to contain a veiled criticism of a contemporary official, likely written as a moral warning about the dangers of exceeding one's proper role in government.
